(xii)  Propose measures to promote financial accountability within the transport sector; 
and 
(xiii)  Develop a best practice guide for transport policy and planning. 

3.  Transport Energy Efficiency Specialist (1 person-month) 

9.  The  emission  of  greenhouse  gases  (GHGs)  produced  by  the  transport  sector  is 
expected to rise rapidly over the coming years, and options need to be developed to address 
this growth at a regional level. Measures must be developed to restrict the transport sector’s 
contributions  to  GHG,  and  these  measures  must  be  embedded  into  strategic  policy  and 
development  frameworks.  In  addition,  the  environmental,  social,  and  economic  viability  of 
transport projects should ensure the broader development of sustainable urban transport. 

10.  The key tasks include but are not be limited to the following areas: 

(i)  Review  current  practices  in  project  evaluation,  within  DMCs,  ADB,  other 
development partners organizations and national governments; 
(ii)  Estimate baseline GHG projections at the regional level; 
(iii)  Develop alternate GHG-mitigation measures at a regional and a country or city 
level; 
(iv)  Provide inputs on GHG for the strategic development framework; 
(v)  Provide inputs for policy issues on GHG reduction; 
